### Issue description

assign `control.MouseMove` event `this.MouseMove += Form1_MouseMove;`

from this event , run the api `ToolTip.Show("string", control, ..)`  or  `ToolTip.Show("string", other_control, ..)` 
then check the MouseMove of control, this will be trigger automaticly even the mouse is stoped.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/da417430-497e-4867-bf16-de46900fce57)

### Steps to reproduce

see my repo [WinFormsToolTipBug](https://github.com/MauNguyenVan/WinFormsToolTipBug)  

```cs
   /// <summary>
   /// Bug 2 tooltip.Show() is allway trigger MouseMove, although the mouse is stopped
   /// </summary>
   /// <param name="sender"></param>
   /// <param name="e"></param>
   private void Form1_MouseMove(object? sender, MouseEventArgs e)
   {
       string txt = "toolTip1.Show(text, window) in Form is allway trigger MouseMove, although the mouse is stopped " + i++;
       toolTip1.IsBalloon = true;
       if (objectBounds.Contains(e.Location))// You can set to true to try more
       {
           if (numericUpDown1.Value == 0)
           {
               toolTip1.Show(txt, this);

           }
           else if (numericUpDown1.Value == 1)
           {
               toolTip1.IsBalloon = false;// If I set  true=> false continuously, the tooltip won't show
               toolTip1.Show(txt, this, e.Location);

           }
           this.Text = txt;
       }
       else
       {
           toolTip1.Hide(this);
       }
   }

```

